Author: brianpribe
Content: Oh I already did yesterday. What lessons did you take out of it?

Author: rickbullotta
Content: A couple things - some when I read it, some more recently.  When I first read it, it made me think that we shouldn't constrain ourselves to conventional or evolutionary approaches to transportation.  I think we've been VERY conventional, and consider self-driving cars very evolutionary, not revolutionary.  It simply automates the current processes.  We need to think bigger about lots of things, not just transportation (as a teenager I actually had some interesting ideas for multi-modal transportation involving pods and carriers that could probably still work today).  It also teaches us the importance of our increasing dependence on technology and knowing how to deal with disruptions.  And obviously lots of messages around "functionalism" and how segments of society value each other (Mike Rowe and I are very much aligned on this).   Interestingly I applied to a couple colleges that were  transportation focused - General Motors Institute (doesn't really exist anymore) and Embry Riddle.  It's still an area that intrigues me.

Author: brianpribe
Content: Constraining to convention and our dependency to it were the lessons I was getting. I‚Äôm taking a bit of a stepped back approach to the theme: transportation of not just physical materials, but also digital information. How do we approach setting up an infrastructure that allows for innovation, reliability, but also maximizing self reliance. For me entropy starts getting involved. How can me minimize our decent towards an inevitable outcome. That being a failing or obsolete infrastructure.

Author: brianpribe
Content: A couple solutions that come to mind: simplicity, efficiency, and minimalism. What is the bare requirement to do this, how efficient can we make this, and how could we do this as simply as possible. However you do need to be cautious with this line of thought because you may stifle innovation. Always have a dreamy ambition of capability. Paired together, these thoughts will drive innovation.

Author: bright_hummingbird_31342
Content:
While it's incredibly impressive technology, I've always wondered whether the self driving technology was over valued.  I believe we're decades off from the technology reaching a reasonable maturity.  We're much more likely to have some sort of hybrid approach with semi-autonomous or dedicated/specialized routes for full autonomous.  As we've seen with the autonomous truck startups, investors love these pipe dreams of automation replacing everything.  They overlook the practical benefits of technology.  It's an "AM / FM" problem.  Investors don't want "actual machine", but "fucking magic" and its associated hype instead.  If anyone has ever worked with computer vision, they'll know how incredibly difficult these problems are.  It's so hard to control or compensate in the real world.  There is weather, dynamic conditions, obstructions, etc.

I would argue their ability to produce compelling products, bring them to market, and command a premium is the value.  They have basically created the prestige of apple products, but in a car.  They've learned to master technology better than others and it shows in their products.  Consumers like the unique experience of owning a Tesla.  In addition to the brand, its leader is unique and is extremely influential.

Author: zackscriven
Content: I think a decade if things go wrong and 5 years if things go right. The current version is getting pretty damn good. Full trips with no interventions, and the rate of improvement is accelerating.  Now with that said, would you atleast agree that FSD alone in a car would have a value of atleast $100k?

Author: bright_hummingbird_31342
Content:
It's extremely good.  It's even better than I thought it could be.  FSD, passing whatever future regulatory muster, will be considerably expensive as an option for a while.  I agree there.

I meant value in terms of an investment in Tesla in general.  It's not that they're not valuable, but valuable for other reasons.  Regarding autonomous driving, I think it's too far out for the technology to sufficiently mature and be in widespread use.  For example, most of the US population resides in the East where there considerably less favorable weather for the technology.  I don't believe this will deliver the value its hyped to have for the foreseeable future.  We've seen too many blunders and "irrational exuberance" in the commercial space where the economic case is arguably most compelling.  I believe more "boring" characteristics like manufacturing competency (e.g., cost, quality, output), product enhancements (e.g., range, connectivity, charging, ownership experience), and brand prestige are more likely to deliver the value.

Content: China's slowdown is hurting everybody. Now we see how much western economies rely on China.... because we are not making a lot of stuff we need. Author: rickbullotta
Content:
Be patient.  There's a reckoning coming in BTC too, once regulation and transparency are introduced.  And you actually point out one of the major flaws of BTC - it's underlying blockchain sucks.  Low transaction rates and high transaction costs, which led to the hack known as Lightning.  Another attack surface - yay!  

I'm long term bullish on multi-party distributed data sharing and on digital payments.  BTC ain't either.  It's just a highly volatile digital investment.

Author: benveenema
Content:
Who is going to regulate Bitcoin? US can for US citizens but not the world. They can't even regulate BitTorrent effectively. How could Bitcoin be more transparent? You can download and audit the entire transaction history and see where the hashing power is. Bitcoin Cash tried to "fix" the Blockchain "issues" but the battery priced that no one cared. The slow and expensive on-chain transaction issues were largely overblown but Lightning is a viable solution. Time will tell if it's a viable layer 2/3 protocol or just a hack.

I think ones overall opinion of Bitcoin comes down to whether one is establishment or anti-establishmemt. Bitcoin is the first, true, people's money. If that's the type of thing that matters to you, you are probably naturally drawn to it.

Author: rickbullotta
Content: Not yet bought in on Lightning, but no doubt some digital innovation will replace ACH processing.  Lightning helps immensely with scalability, transaction cost, and latency, but brings with it some very odd semantics and has some timing-related potential vulnerabilities of its own.  There's also little recourse once a transaction has been fully resolved (e.g. service or product never arrives, fraud, etc.)

Author: nickn5549
Content:
It‚Äôs interesting how Elon can present every thought with equal force, whether it‚Äôs genius or nonsense. He is like a speaker system with the volume stuck at maximum - everything comes out at full blast.
The real problem isn‚Äôt the conviction itself. Conviction is good when you‚Äôre right. The problem is the lack of filtering. When someone delivers every idea with the same intensity, they‚Äôre essentially saying they can‚Äôt tell the difference between their good ideas and their bad ones.
This is particularly dangerous in technology and business. A leader who presents every passing thought as if it‚Äôs the next big breakthrough creates two problems: they make it harder for others to trust their judgment, and they make it nearly impossible for their team to prioritize what matters.
The best thinkers I know have an internal editor. They test their ideas before sharing them. They understand that conviction should be earned through testing and reflection, not applied as a default setting.
Think of it like a dimmer switch versus an on/off button. Good judgment isn‚Äôt about always being right - it‚Äôs about matching your level of conviction to the quality of the idea. Sometimes the right response to your own idea is ‚Äúmaybe‚Äù or ‚Äúlet‚Äôs test that‚Äù rather than ‚Äúabsolutely.‚Äù
The trick isn‚Äôt to have fewer ideas. It‚Äôs to develop the ability to evaluate them before broadcasting them at full volume.

Content:

It's mentioned that Tesla is incorporating some of the dry printing technology in their 4680 batteries.
